I learned something: I didn&#x27;t know that the difference between:<p><pre><code>    function foo() {
    }
</code></pre>
and<p><pre><code>    var foo = function() {
    };
</code></pre>
Was that with the first form foo() will always be declared and available for use inside a scope, while the second form depends at which point it is declared.<p>But I had read somewhere (can&#x27;t remember where... jshint?) a long while ago that using the latter form inside scopes was better, so I&#x27;ve adopted that.<p>I don&#x27;t think I will go with the guide for this one, since not having the function defined automatically is often useful, to avoid overhead of instantiating the function for when it&#x27;s not going to be used due to code flow.
